President Joe Biden has appointed several individuals to key regional leadership positions at the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA), the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA), and the Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD). These appointees will play a crucial role in the President's efforts to rebuild communities affected by the pandemic, economic recovery, and climate change. They bring expertise in their respective areas and have strong relationships with federal, state, tribal, and local leaders. The appointees also reflect the diversity of America and the communities they serve. The USDA appointees include C. John Sullivan III as State Executive Director for the Farm Service Agency in Maryland, Daniel A. Smiarowski as State Executive Director for the Farm Service Agency in Massachusetts, Steve Kouplen as State Executive Director for the Farm Service Agency in Oklahoma, John Litz as State Executive Director for the Farm Service Agency in Tennessee, and John Roberts as State Executive Director for the Farm Service Agency in Vermont. Jonathan McCracken has been appointed as the State Director for Rural Development in Ohio, while Margaret Hoffmann has been appointed as the State Director for Rural Development in Oregon. For FEMA, Lori Ehrlich has been appointed as the Regional Administrator for Region 1, David Warrington for Region 2, and Nancy Dragani for Region 8. Alicka Ampry-Samuel has been appointed as the HUD Regional Administrator for Region 2, and Matthew Heckles for Region 3. Jose Alvarez has been appointed as the HUD Regional Administrator for Region 4, and Ulysses "Deke" Clayborn for Region 7.